purpose, we calculate baryon and dark matter (DM) dynamics in spherical
symmetry, incorporating the self-shielding effects by solving the
radiative transfer of UV radiation. In addition, we prescribe the star
formation in cooled gas components and pursue the dynamics of formed
stars. As a result, we find that the evolution of subgalactic objects in
UV background radiation is separated into three types: (i) prompt star
formation, where less massive clouds
(\~{}10$^{5-8}$M$_{solar}$) are promptly self-shielded and
undergo star formation, (ii) delayed star formation, where photoionized
massive clouds ({\gt}\~{}10$^{8}$M$_{solar}$) collapse despite
high thermal pressure and are eventually self-shielded to form stars in
a delayed fashion, and (iii) supersonic infall, where photoionized less
massive clouds (\~{}10$^{5-8}$M$_{solar}$) contract with
