taken into account. As a result, it is found that when the UV background
radiation is at a level of
10$^{-22}$({$\nu$}/{$\nu$}$_{L}$)$^{-1}$ ergs s$^{-1}$
cm$^{-2}$ Hz$^{-1}$ sr$^{-1}$, the cloud evolution
bifurcates with a critical mass as
M$_{SB}$=2.2{\times}10$^{11}$
M$_{solar}$[(1+z$_{c}$)/5]$^{-4.2}$, where
z$_{c}$ is the final collapse epoch. A cloud more massive than
M$_{SB}$ cools below 5{\times}10$^{3}$ K owing to
H$_{2}$ line emission at the pancake collapse and would undergo
the initial starburst. The pancake possibly evolves into a virialized
system in a dissipationless fashion. Consequently, this leads to the
dissipationless galaxy formation at 3{\lt}\~{}z$_{c}${\lt}\~{}10. A cloud
less massive than M$_{SB}$ cannot cool by H$_{2}$ emission
shortly after the pancake collapse but could cool in the course of
shrinking to the rotation barrier. This is likely to lead to the
dissipational galaxy formation at relatively low redshifts as
0{\lt}\~{}z$_{c}${\lt}\~{}4. The present results provide a solid physical
